🔎 What the project does

Reads the dataset (Rainfall.csv) → This file contains past weather records (temperature, pressure, humidity, etc.) and whether it rained (yes/no).

Trains multiple Machine Learning models → Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Random Forest, KNN.

The best model (highest accuracy) is selected.

Makes Predictions in Two Ways:

From dataset test values → It checks how well the model predicts "rainfall" from the test set.

From user input → You can enter new weather details manually (pressure, temperature, humidity, etc.), and the model will predict YES (it will rain) or NO (it won’t rain).

Saves the trained model → So later, you don’t need to retrain it. You can just load it and directly give input for predictions.

📌 So, does it only give YES/NO?

✅ Yes — the final prediction is binary (two options):

YES → Rain will occur

NO → No rain

The model does not give how much rain (in mm), only the classification (yes/no).

📌 Does it take input from the user?

✅ Yes — in Cell 11, the project allows you to enter your own weather conditions (day, temperature, humidity, etc.), and then it predicts YES/NO for rainfall.

If you don’t want manual input, you can also just test using fixed sample data (Cell 13).

